User Story — Feature Management in Le Comptoir Settings

Title

Feature Toggle Management in Le Comptoir Settings

⸻

User Story

As a Comptoir Manager,
I want to enable or disable specific features and modules directly from the Settings page,
So that I can adapt the Le Comptoir experience to the needs, maturity, and deployment scope of my comptoir without requiring technical intervention.

⸻

Context

Le Comptoir currently already supports configuration for some Microsoft Teams-related features in the Settings section.

The objective of this evolution is to generalize this concept by introducing a centralized “Feature Management” capability allowing managers to activate or deactivate functionalities by category.

This mechanism will support:

* progressive deployments,
* pilot phases,
* local adaptations,
* optional modules,
* and future scalability.

The system must be designed to easily accommodate additional feature categories and features in the future.

⸻

Functional Scope

Feature Management Section

The Settings page must include a dedicated section named:

“Feature Management”

Inside this section, functionalities are grouped by categories and displayed as configurable feature toggles.

⸻

Feature Categories

Category A — Teams Features

Contains existing Teams-related configuration items.

Examples:

* Teams notifications
* Teams integration
* Presence synchronization
* Teams channel features

This category mainly reorganizes existing functionality into the new Feature Management structure.

⸻

Category B — Surveil Tablet Modules

This category controls which modules are available on the Surveil tablet interface.

Examples:

* Visitor queue monitoring
* Coach attendance / time tracking
* Statistics display
* Operational modules
* Future tablet capabilities

When a module is disabled:

* it must not appear on the tablet UI,
* it must not be accessible through navigation or direct access.

⸻

Category C — Global Features

This category controls broader product capabilities impacting complete workflows across Le Comptoir.

Examples:

* Hardware Return workflow
* Asset Traceability workflow
* Signature workflow
* Future end-to-end business processes

When a feature is disabled:

* associated buttons,
* menus,
* entry points,
* and workflows
    must be hidden or inaccessible across the application.

Example:
If “Hardware Return Workflow” is disabled:

* the return hardware journey is not displayed,
* related actions cannot be triggered,
* navigation entries are hidden.

⸻

Feature Administration Permissions

Some features must only be manageable by users with an Administrator role.

In this case:

* Comptoir Managers can still see the feature,
* but cannot modify its state.

The objective is:

* to maintain visibility on available capabilities,
* while clearly indicating that activation/deactivation requires higher privileges.

⸻

UX Expectations

General Layout

The Feature Management section should provide:

* clear visual separation between categories,
* scalable organization,
* intuitive ON/OFF interactions,
* support for future expansion.

Suggested UX patterns:

* grouped cards,
* accordion/collapsible sections,
* toggle switches,
* category headers.

⸻

UX Expectations for Restricted Features

When a feature is restricted to Administrators:

Visual Behavior

The feature must appear visually distinct from editable features.

Possible UX patterns:

* reduced opacity,
* disabled toggle state,
* lock icon,
* different background styling,
* tooltip or info icon.

The restriction must be understandable immediately.

⸻

Information Message

A contextual explanation must indicate why the feature cannot be modified.

Example:

“This feature can only be managed by an Administrator.”

The explanation may appear:

* on hover,
* via tooltip,
* through an information icon (“i”),
* or inline below the feature.

⸻

Behavior Rules

When a Feature is Enabled

* the functionality becomes immediately available,
* related UI elements are displayed,
* users can access the workflow/module normally.

⸻

When a Feature is Disabled

* the functionality is hidden from the UI,
* direct access is blocked,
* associated actions cannot be triggered.

⸻

Restricted Features

For Administrators

* the toggle is editable,
* the state can be modified normally.

For Managers without sufficient permissions

* the feature remains visible,
* the current state remains visible,
* the toggle is not editable,
* interaction does not modify the state,
* an explanatory message is available.

⸻

Permissions

Only authorized roles can modify feature toggles.

Expected roles:

* Administrator
* Comptoir Manager (limited depending on feature permissions)

Standard users/coaches must not access Feature Management settings.

⸻

Technical / Architectural Expectations

The implementation should:

* support easy addition of future categories,
* support easy addition of future features,
* avoid hardcoded logic whenever possible,
* centralize feature configuration,
* expose feature states consistently across frontend and backend.

The architecture should ideally support:

* feature-driven rendering,
* feature-driven authorization,
* future API-driven configuration,
* scalable feature governance.

⸻

Acceptance Criteria

AC1 — Feature Management Section

Given I am an authorized user
When I open the Settings page
Then I can access a “Feature Management” section.

⸻

AC2 — Categorized Features

Given the Feature Management section
When it is displayed
Then features are grouped by categories:

* Teams Features
* Surveil Tablet Modules
* Global Features.

⸻

AC3 — Toggle Interaction

Given an editable feature toggle
When I activate or deactivate it
Then the new state is saved and applied.

⸻

AC4 — Hidden Disabled Features

Given a feature is disabled
When a user accesses the application
Then related UI elements and workflows are hidden or inaccessible.

⸻

AC5 — Surveil Tablet Module Visibility

Given a Surveil tablet module is disabled
When the tablet interface is displayed
Then the module does not appear.

⸻

AC6 — Global Workflow Deactivation

Given the Hardware Return workflow is disabled
When a user accesses Le Comptoir
Then all related entry points and actions are unavailable.

⸻

AC7 — Permissions

Given a standard user
When accessing Settings
Then Feature Management controls are not visible.

⸻

AC8 — Restricted Feature Visibility

Given a feature restricted to Administrators
When a Comptoir Manager opens Feature Management
Then the feature is visible but not editable.

⸻

AC9 — Visual Identification of Restricted Features

Given a restricted feature
When displayed to a non-admin user
Then the feature appears visually differentiated from editable features.

⸻

AC10 — Restriction Explanation

Given a restricted feature
When a non-admin user interacts with it
Then an explanatory message indicates that Administrator rights are required.

⸻

UX / Design Topics for Discovery

Topics to explore with UX:

* Should categories be collapsible?
* Should there be search/filter capability for future scalability?
* Should features display descriptions/tooltips?
* Should changes require confirmation?
* Should changes be audited/logged?
* Should some features depend on others?
* Should disabled features optionally appear as “coming soon”?

⸻

Future Considerations (Out of Scope for V1)

Potential future extensions:

* Feature dependencies
* Country-level inheritance
* Scheduled activation/deactivation
* Temporary feature activation
* Beta/Pilot labels
* Usage analytics per feature
* Central administration across multiple comptoirs
* Environment-specific feature flags
* Gradual rollout mechanisms
